Korea-Bulgarian Summit on Cooperation in Nuclear Power Plants and Defense Industries (Bulgarian) | Yahoo!
(SEOUL=Yonhap News) South Korean President Moon Jae-in met with Bulgarian Prime Minister Borisov on his official visit to Korea on September 27 to discuss ways to expand bilateral cooperation.
This was the first time the Prime Minister of Bulgaria visited Korea.
President Moon welcomed the visit to Korea before the 30th anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic relations next year and appreciated the leadership of Prime Minister Borisov, who leads the development of Bulgaria.
The two leaders appreciated the continued increase in trade and investment between the two countries amid growing protectionist tradeism globally, and agreed to work together to expand economic cooperation in the future.
President Moon welcomed Bulgaria's policy of granting Korean companies the status of "strategic investors" and said he hoped that this would facilitate Korean companies' investment in Bulgaria.
In addition, he emphasized that Korea can become the best partner of Bulgaria as Bulgaria promotes the introduction of nuclear power plants and the modernization of defense, and called for attention and cooperation so that Korean companies can participate in the order of the Bulgarian government's nuclear power plants and the promotion of the defense industry.
In addition, the two leaders agreed to strengthen future-oriented cooperation in the areas of battery and auto parts for electric vehicles and renewable energy.
Prime Minister Borisov hoped that Korea's leading ICT (information and communication technology) and science, technology and education sectors would cooperate closely.
They also discussed the Korean Peninsula's peace process, and President Moon expressed his gratitude for the support of the Korean government's efforts for peace consolidation on the Korean Peninsula, including Bulgaria's announcement of support for the North-South and North-America Summits.
Prime Minister Borisov appreciated President Moon's will to build a peace regime on the Korean Peninsula and the efforts of the Korean government, and reiterated the firm support of the Bulgarian government.
The meeting was attended by Jo Yunmo, Secretary of the Ministry of Trade, Industry and Energy, Lee Ho-houn, Chief Secretary of the Economic Affairs Bureau, Chong Chong, and Kim Hyun-jong, Second Director of the National Security Office.
The first secretary of the Department of Foreign Affairs, Cho Se-young, also attended the meeting.
Local industry in Hyogo and Awaji Island, Kinki Ceramics Co., Ltd., a manufacturer of "Awaji tiles," filed for quasi-self-insolvency debt of approximately 2 billion yen (Imperial Data Bank) - Yahoo!
It was also affected by the sluggish housing market and the progress of "consumer tile roofing away" due to repeated damage from the earthquake.
Kinki Ceramics Co., Ltd. (TDB Corporation Code: 530173983, capitalized 9.92 million yen, 881-8 Otani, Awaji City, Hyogo Prefecture, representative Yukizo Fukuhara, 44 employees) filed for quasi-self-bankruptcy at the Kobe District Court on August 30.
The applicant is Daichi Yoshida (1-10-8 Nishitenman, Kita Ward, Osaka City, Osaka Prefecture), and one other attorney.
The company was founded in June 1895 and reorganized as a corporation in April 1961.
At first, he started his business as a manufacturer of ibushi tiles, a local industry in Awaji Island, in Nishitan-cho, Mihara County (now Minamiawaji City) under the trade name of Kinki Kiln Co., Ltd.
In October 1986, Kyowa Kiln Co., Ltd. merged into Kyowa Kiln Co., Ltd., succeeded the business of Kinki Sangyo Co., Ltd., and at the same time, the head office was moved to its present location after changing its present trade name.
After that, sales offices were established in Fukuyama City, Hiroshima City, Oita City, Miyazaki City, etc., and it became the current system, and Ibushi-gawara was mainly used before, but due to changes in consumer needs, Western-style tiles such as flat plate tiles were manufactured at 70% and Ibushi-gawara was manufactured at 30%.
The company has built a wide range of sales bases mainly in western Japan, including major house manufacturers, construction materials trading companies, and roof construction companies.
He was well known as the top tile maker of Awaji Island.
However, demand was sluggish due to the sluggish housing market following the Lehman shock and the severe damage caused by the Great East Japan Earthquake and the Kumamoto Earthquake, which caused consumers to leave their roofs.
On the profit side, in addition to a decline in the profit margin due to the surge in fuel prices, the company suffered a continuous deficit due to excessive interest-bearing debt associated with inventory burdens and business fixed investment, and was forced to carry out severe financing.
For this reason, although the Bank sought to rebuild its business by requesting financial institutions to ease the conditions for repayment of loans, there were no signs of recovery in business conditions, and funding gradually became tight.
I couldn't help but give up on business continuity and this is the measure.
The debt is currently under investigation, but it is expected to be about 2 billion yen.
Prefectural Dinosaur Museum in Katsuyama City, Fukui Prefecture, which promotes "industrialization of tourism" (photographed by Japanese aerial photographs and small drones)
Katsuyama City, Fukui Prefecture, announced on September 25 that it will acquire approximately 25,000 square meters of land adjacent to the construction site of the road station "Dinosaur Valley Katsuyama," which will open next spring.
In order to accelerate the "industrialization of tourism" advocated by the city and the local economy, it aims to attract accommodation-specific hotels and restaurants.
On the same day, the board members explained to the Special Committee on the Improvement of the City Council's Invitational Base.
With the opening of the Hokuriku Shinkansen in the spring of 2023, as well as the opening of the entire section of the Chubu Jukan Expressway within the prefecture, as well as the expansion and renovation of the prefectural Dinosaur Museum (Katsuyama City), the city intends to promote a shift from a day-trip center to a stay-style sightseeing and attract accommodation.
It is a private idle land located next to the east of the road station construction site.
Surrounded by the Kuzuryu River, Takinami River, and prefectural roads, it is more than twice as large as a roadside station (about 12,000 square meters).
In the name of the industrial complex, the City Land Development Corporation will proceed with land negotiations from this fiscal year, acquire land, and build land in FY21.
According to the city, private businesses such as farmers' restaurants and harvest experience facilities, fast food, and restaurants are already looking to enter the market.
As for accommodation, it was also revealed that Sekisui House has promoted its name as a city to attract accommodation-specific hotels adjacent to Michi No Eki, which is planned throughout Japan.
Sekisui House is scheduled to expand into three locations within Fukui Prefecture, but there are other cities and towns that are willing to attract and may compete.
The city also plans to build a parking lot.
Some members called for speed-up when the maintenance schedule was slow, and others said that there was no place to sleep.
Vice Mayor Sanekio Mizukami stated that he would like to promote the superiority of Katsuyama City by putting the prefectural dinosaur museum and ski jam Katsuyama in front of the industrial complex on the theme of tourism.
