"Korea wants to return to GSOMIA" U.S. Assistant Secretary of State (Sankei Shimbun) - Yahoo!
U.S. Undersecretary of State for South Korea and Japan, Napper, in an interview with the Sankei Shimbun at the U.S. Ambassador's residence in Tokyo, said on November 27 that "Korea hopes to reconsider and come back to the decision to destroy Japan and Korea's comprehensive military information protection agreement (GSOMIA), which expires on November 23."
It is unusual for a high-ranking U.S. official to mention a reconsideration of GSOMIA's destruction.
GSOMIA is based on the agreement between Japan, South Korea, the United States, the United States, and South Korea to share missile launch information.
In August, Korea announced that it would destroy the agreement with Japan, and if it expires, the framework for protecting military information will collapse.
Napper argued that "without GSOMIA, we cannot effectively respond to the crisis."
"There is time until the revocation," he strongly urged the return of Korea.
He also pointed out that the joint flight training conducted by China and Russia in July over the Sea of Japan was "the first time in history" and stressed that "it is essential that the United States, Korea and Japan, which share values such as democracy and human rights, collaborate in alliance relations."
He pointed out that the recent deterioration in Japan-Korea relations "damaged the national interests of the United States."
"There is no intention of intermediation," he said, "Japan and Korea will play a positive role to fill the gap."
