Tokaimura Critical Accident, 20 years in 30 days, 300 nuclear facility troubles: Hokkaido Shimbun
According to an interview with the Nuclear Regulation Authority (NRA), 336 cases of accidents and failures at nuclear facilities across Japan were reported from fiscal 2000 to fiscal 2006 following the critical accident in Tokai-mura, Ibaraki Prefecture, the first in Japan's history of nuclear power.
It has been 30 days and 20 years since the critical accident that alarmed the safety myth of the nuclear industry.
According to the report, although the level 0 (non-safety critical) and non-assessment issues accounted for about 90% of the respondents who reported seriousness, it is necessary to continuously raise safety awareness based on lessons learned from the accident and the accident at TEPCO's Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant in 2011.
Koichi Soda, who has completed the story and original drawings of creative picture books, is seeking donations for publication.
Koichi Soda (64), an artist from the Echizen City Regional Development Cooperation Volunteer in Fukui Prefecture, started a crowdfunding campaign aimed at publishing creative picture books inspired by legends in Fukui Prefecture in order to promote town development using picture books.
Mr. Soda, who was originally from Hokkaido and started his activities as a member of the cooperative group in April this year, says, "I want to convey the hearts of the people of Fukui based on deep faith through picture books."
[Donation is here] To convey the heart of Fukui.
While Mr. Soda is active as an artist working on contemporary art based on mathematics, he has also been active as a member of the cooperative team since the end of the calendar.
After working on the town development of Nagano, Kumamoto and Tochigi, he joined Echizen City in April this year.
In the same city that produced Riko Kako and Chihiro Iwasaki, he aims to create a town that makes use of picture books.
Mr. Soda lived in the city and said, "I was surprised by the depth of compassion I could understand for the first time."
What attracted attention was the legend of Awara City, "The face of the demon of the bride Odoshi."
It is a story that a gentle-hearted bride continues to chant Nenbutsu (Buddhist invocation) to help her mother without worrying about the fact that she was surprised by the face of an ogre.
"I forgot my hatred and returned with kindness and kindness, and I felt the origin of the faith and kindness of the people of Fukui."
Inspired by the original picture book, Soda went to Yoshizaki Gobo in Awara City as soon as he arrived to complete the story "Meoto Oni" where a loving couple of demons and a boy appear.
From June, he drew 10 scenes with warm watercolors, taking advantage of his job, and the materials of picture books were scattered.
In addition, the cover of the picture book will be made with washi using Echizen washi, a traditional craft that lives in Echizen City.
This leads to an opportunity for parents and children to enjoy the touch of washi through reading and listening.
The goal of the donation is 850,000 yen for 600 copies.
The deadline is 25 October.
Mr. Soda said, "Fukui's heart, which has been nurtured under the historical Buddhist culture, is proud throughout Japan.
I want to tell children what true kindness and compassion have been handed down through picture books."
It is one of the projects that Fukui Prefecture certifies 11 projects for regional revitalization that are challenged by local cooperatives and businesses in the prefecture, and supports using hometown tax.
The Bank of Japan (Fukui Shimbun) provides information, and the Bank of Fukui cooperates with management support.
