Sakura shrimp in the growth process PT in Shizuoka City, etc., taken 290 meters deep | Shizuoka Shimbun at Es
Sakura shrimp born this year was successfully photographed in the deep sea of Suruga Bay.
The Yui Sakura Ebi Project, a project of the Ocean Industry Cluster Council led by industry, academia, and government in Shizuoka City, succeeded in photographing sakura shrimp, which is thought to have been born during the spawning season this spring and summer, at a depth of 290 meters in Suruga Bay.
The video of the growth process is valuable, and the people concerned want to lead to the elucidation of the ecology of sakura shrimp, which has many mysteries.
The photograph was taken near the bottom of the sea about 1 to 5 km off the coast of the Kamahara district, Shimizu Ward.
A total of 300 were confirmed in 17 minutes.
In the daytime, the conventional knowledge that sakura shrimp in the deep sea form a certain group at the bottom of the sea was reestablished.
The adult body is about 40 mm long and the individual reflected is about 23 mm long.
The spawning period was identified by collating with seasonal data of freshly caught sakura shrimp.
Detailed analysis is requested by Fujitsu Software Technologies and Shizuoka Technical College, which comprise the team.
Keisuke Mizuno, Project Leader, said, "I want to capture the living figure of individuals in the growth process, including fry."
Mother Ranch resumes, Chiba residents are free of charge Damaged by Typhoon by the end of October | Shizuoka Shimbun at Es
Chiba-kun, the mascot character of Chiba Prefecture, welcomes visitors at the Mother Ranch, which has reopened its business.
Mother Ranch in Futsu City, Chiba Prefecture, which had been closed since 9 days due to power outages and damage to facilities caused by Typhoon No. 15, resumed operations on 28th.
Residents in Chiba Prefecture are free to enter the affected areas by the end of October.
Many people visited the park at the same time as the opening of the park, and at the entrance gate, the mascot character of the prefecture "Chiba-kun" who ran to cheer was welcomed.
The roof was covered with blue sheets and some facilities continued to be repaired, but half of the restaurants were forced to restart.
Kenji Mitani (34), a family member of Sagamihara City, said with a smile, "I was worried about when I would resume.I came to enjoy the event of potato digging because I thought it would lead to reconstruction."
