Men's Singles (Bad × Spi).
The Japan national team, who won six medals at the 25th World Championships in Basel, Switzerland, at the big event in badminton in August, finished the training camp in early September and entered the China OP (Joshu/Super1000) starting from 17th.
Here, while looking back at the first half of the Olympic race between May and August, which started next year's Tokyo Olympics, we will look forward to the men's singles for the middle race (September to December).
The Badminton Olympic Games, which began in May, culminated in four of the world's top athletes competing in the Super 500 and above.
In the first half of the competition, the two players were Kento Momota, who won 2 of the 4 races, and Tensei (Cho Tien Cheng) of Taiwan.
Momota won the World Championship and Shutensei won the Indonesia OP (S1000) and the World Ranking Point, which is directly connected to the Olympic race.
Momota also controls Japan OP (S750).
The tournament has been held since May, including the Sudirman Cup (May in China), the Indonesia OP (July in Indonesia), the Japan OP (July in Japan), and the World Championships (August in Japan).
Although the number of players is small compared to other top players, it is a schedule that reduces the burden on the body.
In August, only one World Championships were held, so fatigue would not be greater than during the war.
It is expected that the best results will be obtained in the mid-term battle in which the top tournaments since September will continue.
A strong Taiwanese ace.
Also attention to young Thai people!
Shutensei, who also won the top tournament of Indonesia OP and Thailand OP (S500), has already participated in seven tournaments.
In September, he participated in the local Taipei OP (S300) and won the championship.
As a result, the player has a strong physical strength and does not suffer a series of battles.
Even after the tournament, there is no major problem in the performance of the game.
Rather, being able to score high points in the first half of the tournament will make it easier to adjust the schedule for the upcoming tournament.
Shutensei had an impression that it lacked explosive power until last year, but this year, the stability in the field of play increased, and it became possible to continue the good performance firmly.
For Momota, who is ranked No. 1 in the world ranking, it seems to be a more troublesome opponent than ever.
In addition to these two players, the first half of the game was won by Thailand's young Ace Cantaphone and India's Cy Planis B.
Anders Antonsen, who is fighting alone as a European, is the three players.
Although Cantaphone does not advance to the final at the top level, he has the power to advance to the top, such as entering the best 4 at the second round of this season.
Although there is still a rough side, the 20-year-old (21-year-old on 18th) who has become able to rally on equal terms with top players has a great potential to leap in the Olympic race.
Cy Pranice B. has also taken a step out of India, where singles have good players.
