On September 26, the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare (MHLW) announced for the first time the names of 424 public hospitals in 1455 public hospitals and public hospitals in Japan, including Japan and the Red Cross, which judged that their medical records were poor.
In Fukui Prefecture, the Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare examined the treatment results of 14 public and public hospitals, and four facilities were targeted: Awa Hospital, the National Hospital Organization of Awa City, and Awa Hospital, respectively.
⇒4 hospitals subject to reorganization: standards are wrong
In order to prevent medical expenses from expanding due to the aging population, it was necessary to promote reorganization and integration with hospitals in competing areas.
In October, we will request a full-scale review of reorganization and integration at the target hospital, and we will conclude by September next year.
Although there is no compulsion force, it is expected that local chiefs and residents will be repulsed due to anxiety that nearby hospitals will disappear.
It was announced at the meeting on the same day.
The total number of hospitals targeted was 29.1%, with relatively few beds.
By prefecture, the percentage was higher in Niigata (53.7%), Hokkaido (48.6%), Miyagi (47.5%), Yamaguchi (46.7%), and Okayama (43.3%).
The number of targets was 54 in Hokkaido, and Okinawa was the only zero.
Based on data from FY2017, the Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare investigated 1455 hospitals in public and public hospitals that can respond to "advanced acute phase" for severe patients and "acute phase" for general surgery.
We analyzed nine medical records such as cancer and emergency medical care, and whether competing hospitals were located within 20 minutes by car, and judged the necessity of publicizing the hospital name.
The hospital should be considered to be abolished and some departments should be transferred to other hospitals.
Medical expenses increased rapidly in 25 years, when all baby boomers were 75 years old or older.
For this reason, the Ministry of Health, Labor and Welfare aims to reduce the number of beds in hospitals with 1,246,000 beds (18 years) to 119,11,000 beds nationwide.
Currently, there are many beds in the "high-acute" and "acute" periods where nurses are placed thickly and medical expenses are required, while there is a shortage of rehabilitation services that require high needs for elderly people.
In order to cope with the aging population, it is necessary not only to reduce the number of beds, but also to increase rehabilitation.
For the reorganization and consolidation of hospitals, each prefecture formulated a "regional medical concept" that defined the number of beds required for 25 years.
Although the country is divided into 339 districts, municipalities and medical officials are discussing it, many local residents and chiefs remain cautious and the discussion is difficult.
The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare wants to revitalize the discussion by publishing the names of hospitals with poor results.
Comprehensive drill for disaster prevention such as the assumption of Mt.Komagatake eruption, road, wide area with participation of residents for the first time in 18 years (video): Hokkaido Shimbun
On September 27, a comprehensive disaster prevention drill was held in the forest, Nanae, and Kabe-cho in the Toshima-kan.
Approximately 400 people attended the event, including officials and residents of 20 institutions including roads and three towns.
It was held for the first time since the Hokkaido Komagatake Volcano Disaster Prevention Council formulated an evacuation plan incorporating evacuation routes for residents in August.
It has been 18 years since the local residents participated in extensive training.
It is assumed that Mt. Komagatake erupted at 8:45 a.m. and the mud flow reached the town at the foot of the mountain.
When the level of volcanic alert was raised to 5 (evacuation), evacuation shelters were opened in Mori and Nanae towns, and residents moved by buses and police cars prepared by each town.
100,000 students protest against school holidays against global warming - Yahoo!
About 100,000 citizens, mainly students who sympathized with 16-year-old environmental activist Greta Tunberg, marched in Vancouver on September 27 to protest climate change.
Climate demonstrations in Vancouver
The march took place from Vancouver City Hall across Canby Bridge to the downtown library.
A few hours before the start of the meeting, people with placards began to gather in front of the city hall.
More than 100,000 people attended the event.
The police also cooperated with the police on the road along the way, keeping watch over all the people for hours.
In conjunction with the United Nations Climate Action Summit held in New York, the city of Vancouver has held many events to consider global warming since last weekend.
On the 27th of the last day, a school strike was held on Friday for the future.
The students who took part in the school on this day complained to adults, "I want to protect the earth even if I take a break from the school," and many adults who took part in the work off responded, "We will do our best for the future of children who are seriously studying."
Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries (Gifu Shimbun Web) - Yahoo!
The Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries (MAFF) released on July 27 a proposal to revise the quarantine guidelines to prevent the spread of the infection of Ton cholera, an infectious disease of livestock.
The province will select nine prefectures, including Gifu Prefecture and Aichi Prefecture, which have been confirmed to be infected with pigs and wild boars.
Vaccination of live pigs and fertilized eggs is restricted to the region, but distribution outside the meat and processed foods is permitted.
After making public comments to the general public (an open call for opinions), we aim to complete the procedure as early as October.
By using vaccines and allowing extraterritorial distribution such as meat, it is no longer a "clean country" certified by international organizations and may affect the export of pork.
Since the outbreak of September last year, Japan has temporarily suspended its status as a pure country.
In the revised plan, the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries set up a "Vaccination Recommended Area" based on experts' opinions regarding areas with high risk of infection from wild boar to pigs.
The prefecture in question creates a "vaccination program" that summarizes the scope, time, number of heads, how to proceed, etc.
Saitama, Toyama, Ishikawa, Fukui, Nagano, Mie, Shiga are the seven other prefectures that are recommended for vaccination.
When the guidelines have been revised, the region will review the situation and make decisions extremely once again.
The movement of inoculated pigs, semen, fertilized eggs, corpses, excretions, etc. is limited in principle to the region.
As for meat and processed products, they are not targeted based on the cost of distribution restrictions and the impact on farmers, and they effectively tolerate distribution outside the region.
In order to prevent viruses from spreading, we will thoroughly process food waste.
He also advocates the safety of inoculated pigs and works to prevent harmful rumors.
The draft amendments to the Guidelines were compiled at a meeting of experts held on the same day and confirmed at a meeting of the Anti-Defection Control Headquarters.
In the future, we will conduct opinion inquiries and public comments to prefectures until October 7 and implement new quarantine guidelines.
