The outline of the construction of the children's playground facility and Minaminumahara Elementary School will be decided in Yamagata City | Yamagata Shimbun
The bidders for the children's play facilities and Minaminumahara Elementary School, which Yamagata City is planning to build using the PFI (Social Capital Improvement) method by utilizing private funds, were decided, and an outline of the facility was explained at the Standing Committee of the City Council held on October 26.
Image of a new children's play facility in Kataya, Yamagata City
The children's play facility is scheduled to be built on the north side of Yamagata Kuchu in Katayachi District, with an area of approximately 23400 square meters.
The building is a steel building with a total floor area of about 3,000 square meters.
It has a semi-underground gymnasium, café, and book corner.
It also features universal design playground equipment for children with disabilities to play outdoors, ensuring 300 parking spaces.
A committee meeting was held at the city hall on 5th of this month, and 13 shelter groups (Yamagata City) won the bid for 30.5 million yen including design, preparation for opening, maintenance and operation expenses for 15 years.
Design and construction will begin in January next year, and it is scheduled to open in March 2022.
Image of Minaminumabara Elementary School
The school has over 900 pupils.
It is planned to be built on the north side of the current school building in Iizawa City, and the site area is about 21,500 square meters.
It is a three-story reinforced concrete building with a total floor area of approximately 8580 square meters.
There are 30 classrooms, including two pools, a steel gymnasium and a post-school children's club.
At the review committee meeting on June 6, the Ichimura Corporation Group (Yamagata City), consisting of eight companies, won the bid for 4.512.1 million yen including design, demolition costs for the old school building, and maintenance and operation costs for 15 years.
It was designed and built in December and is expected to be completed in October 2010.
