Onsarigo worked as a pacemaker for Nagai and elementary school students on land, and three people updated the tournament record|Yamagata Shimbun
Children run at 800 meters.
On the left is Joseph Onsarigo, a pacemaker.
The goodwill track competition for Nagai City Elementary School was held on the 26th at the Koyo Seiki Athlete Field Nagai (city track and field stadium) in Nagai, and Joseph Onsarigo (27), a long-distance runner belonging to Nasu Construction (city of Nagai), was a pacemaker.
With a light run, three new records of the tournament were set up.
Onsarigo pulled the children in a total of four races, 1000 meters for men and 800 meters for women.
The first-ranked Chiya Koseki (Hirano Ko 6) was 3 minutes 4.38 seconds, the first-ranked Ransei Shigara (Isazawa Ko 6) was 2 minutes 34.17 seconds, and the second-ranked Rinsan Asano (Nagai Ko 6) was 2 minutes 35.73 seconds.
Mr. Koseki said, "It was hard to talk about fast Onsarigo players, but I was able to endure it."
Onsarigo said, "The children were good at running, and I had a perfect job."
The event was organized by the Nagai City Elementary School Sports Promotion Association to promote friendship among sixth grade elementary school students in the city.
